=E2=80=9925 Fashion Predictions, Tiger=E2=80=99s Indoor Game,
The WaPo Exodus
-------------------------------------------------

Welcome back to The Daily Courant, your afternoon medley of Puck=E2=80=99s
best new reporting.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

First up today, Lauren Sherman gazes into her crystal ball and opens her re=
porter=E2=80=99s notebook to prognosticate the major themes propelling the =
fashion industry in =E2=80=9925: What does Matthieu Blazy=E2=80=99s Chanel =
appointment portend for the luxury landscape? Are department stores toast? =
And how far will formerly #resistance-friendly,
Trump-detesting industry leaders go to avoid getting tariffed into oblivion=
?

=C2=A0

Plus, below the fold: John Ourand chats with golf gurus Joe House and Natha=
n Hubbard about the overstretched PGA Tour and whether the sport is headed =
for a =E2=80=9925 upswing. Scott Mendelson offers a timely post-mortem of t=
he holiday box office. And Tara
Palmeri sits down with presidential historian Douglas Brinkley to consider =
how the record books will portray Joe Biden.

Meanwhile, on the pods=E2=80=A6 John Heilemann and non-fiction master Wrigh=
t Thompson discuss why the story of Emmett Till matters more than ever. On =
The Grill Room, Dylan Byers and Semafor co-founder Ben Smith survey next ye=
ar=E2=80=99s media
landscape. On Fashion People, Lauren and Sara Shapiro assess the future of =
America=E2=80=99s mall brands, changes at Chanel, and luxury price hikes. A=
nd on The Powers That Be, Bill Cohan joins Ben Landy to discuss how Apple, =
Amazon, and Alphabet have forced legacy TV incumbents to countenance their =
